Constructing a BNF-Style Short-Term Trading Fund: A Step-by-Step Framework for Disciplined, Emotion-Proof Intraday Momentum Trading

Tom Brennan¹ and Sophia Entwood²  
¹ Principal, BNF Fund  
² Fund Administrator, BNF Fund  
March 1, 2026 (Revised & Final Polish)

Abstract  
Most retail trading accounts lack structure, discipline, and longevity. Traders chase moves, average down, hold overnight, and eventually blow up. This paper presents a step-by-step framework for building a BNF-style short-term trading fund focused on exploiting emotional over-reactions (fear and greed) in liquid leveraged ETFs. The process emphasizes tiny risk per trade, volume as king, patience, single decisive entry, fast cuts on losers, partial profit-taking on winners, and fully mechanical execution with no overnight holds. Key components include explicit entry filters, mechanical exits, strength ratings, macro/event risk pre-checks, and an optional Meta-Kaizen evolution layer for continuous refinement. The result is a living, reproducible system that is executable by non-experts, successor-ready, and designed for multi-year compounding through consistent, low-frequency, high-conviction trades (1–3 trades per week maximum). Abstracted examples, worked calculations, and checklists are provided so readers can construct their own version.

Keywords: BNF trading, short-term momentum, fear/greed exploitation, rules-based trading, capital preservation, Meta-Kaizen, emotion-proof execution, intraday trading, leveraged ETFs

1. Introduction  
Short-term trading accounts are often chaotic, emotional, and short-lived. Traders chase every move, average down on losers, hold overnight, and eventually blow up. This paper offers a practical, step-by-step framework for building a BNF-style short-term trading fund that is:  
- Rules-based and fully mechanical  
- Focused on emotional over-reactions confirmed by volume  
- Designed for intraday trades only (no overnights)  
- Built for survival and compounding over years  
- Executable by non-experts (successor-ready)  
- Capable of autonomic evolution through Meta-Kaizen  

The framework is drawn from real-world application but presented in abstracted, reproducible form so any investor can adapt it to their own temperament and account size.

2. Core Philosophy & Literature Positioning  
A BNF-style short-term trading fund rests on a small set of interlocking principles:  
- Volume is king — only trade when participation confirms conviction  
- Tiny risk per trade — survive at all costs  
- Wait for emotional extremes — fear dips or greed surges  
- Single decisive entry — no adds, no averaging down  
- Cut losers fast — no hope trading  
- Let winners run with partial profit-taking — lock gains systematically  
- No overtrading — quality over quantity (1–3 high-conviction trades per week maximum)  
- Emotionless execution — system over feelings  
- Compound patiently — 8–10 year horizon  

These principles contrast with common retail trading practices: high-frequency day trading, averaging down, overnight holds, and emotional overrides. BNF (Takashi Kotegawa) demonstrated that starting small, risking tiny amounts, waiting for high-conviction setups, and executing mechanically can compound a modest account into significant wealth over years. Minervini and other momentum traders add technical confirmation, while Covey and Taleb reinforce discipline and antifragility.

3. Step-by-Step Construction Process  

Step 1: Define the Conviction Thesis  
Write a clear, falsifiable thesis answering:  
- What emotional market dynamic will I exploit? (fear/greed over-reactions in leveraged ETFs)  
- Why is this edge repeatable? (volume confirms participation, leverage amplifies moves)  
- What is the risk tolerance? (tiny per trade, no overnight risk)  
- What return expectation is realistic? (consistent small edges compounding over years)  

Example thesis (abstracted): “Markets are driven by fear and greed. Leveraged ETFs amplify these emotions, creating outsized intraday opportunities when confirmed by volume. Tiny risk, patience, and mechanical execution allow compounding over years (1–3 high-conviction trades per week maximum).”

Step 2: Select the Instrument Universe  
Choose 20–30 high-volume leveraged ETFs (2× and 3× bull/bear) with strong liquidity.  
Criteria:  
- Consistent average daily volume (minimum 5–10 million shares)  
- Tight spreads for instant fills/exits  
- Sector diversity (tech, semis, broad indexes, niche on standby)  
- Avoid illiquid or low-float names  

Example universe (10 representative LETFs): TQQQ, SQQQ, SOXL, SPXL, SPXS, UPRO, TNA, QLD, NVDL, TSLL.

Holdings remain fixed unless quarterly survival filter removes weak performers.

Step 3: Build Entry Rules  
Three non-negotiable filters (all must pass):  
- Absolute % change from prior close ≥ +3.0% (greed surge for bear ETFs) or ≤ –3.0% (fear dip for bull ETFs)  
- Volume > 2.0× 20-day average daily volume (calculated as cumulative volume at time of signal vs. 20-day avg)  
- Clear momentum direction: For fear dips — BTF bounce confirmed by 5-min bar close above prior low or VWAP reclaim after fear dip; for greed surges — breakout below recent high on volume  

Strength ratings (1–3) determine risk level and trailing stop tightness.

Step 4: Layer Protection Mechanisms  
- Risk per trade: 1% max (2% only on Level 3 extremes)  
- Hard position cap: 25% of account per trade  
- Mechanical exits: Fixed trailing stop (3.5% Level 1, 4% Level 2/3 from intraday high); scale-out locks partial gains while letting remainder run  
- Hard close: All positions sold by 4:00 PM ET  
- Pre-checks: Market direction, financial calendar, political/institutional risk flags (avoid FOMC days, major earnings blackouts, geopolitical headlines)  

Cash held in money market when no qualifiers.

Step 5: Add Governance & Evolution Layer  
- Weekly trade log and review (win rate, gain/loss ratio)  
- Quarterly watchlist survival filter (drop bottom 10% weakest performers)  
- Optional Meta-Kaizen scan (novelty-driven improvements via KVS scoring; KVS scores ≥0.5 surface potential refinements to entry filters, stop levels, or pod size during quarterly sharpening)  

Ideas scoring ≥0.5 auto-surfaced for principal review. All changes require written approval and log entry.

4. Worked Archetype Example  
Abstracted BNF-style short-term fund:  
- Thesis: Exploit fear/greed in liquid leveraged ETFs (1–3 high-conviction trades per week maximum)  
- Universe: 20–30 high-volume LETFs (e.g., TQQQ, SQQQ, SOXL, SPXL, SPXS, UPRO, TNA, QLD, SSO, NVDL, TSLL)  
- Entry: 3 filters (move size, volume, direction)  
- Protection: 1% risk, 25% position cap, 4% trailing stop, EOD close  
- Evolution: Weekly review + quarterly survival filter + optional Meta-Kaizen scan  

Reader adapts by substituting their own risk tolerance, account size, and broker rules.

5. Implementation Notes & Common Pitfalls  
- Start simple: Build core filters and exits first, add pre-checks iteratively  
- Avoid over-optimization: Rules must survive regime shifts  
- Document everything: Thesis, rules, changes — successor must understand why  
- Pitfalls: Emotional override, chasing volume-less moves, overnight holds, increasing frequency  

6. Conclusion  
A BNF-style short-term trading fund is a living, mechanical system — not a set-it-and-forget-it template. By following this framework, investors can build a disciplined vehicle that exploits emotional over-reactions, protects capital, and compounds patiently over years. Adapt it to your own temperament and account. *The process is as important as the product.*

